definition.value: A single species pathogen growth phenotype in which the size of pathogen penetration stuctures are increased when assessed for penetration ability on a given experimental substance/membrane.
A single species pathogen growth phenotype in which the size of pathogen penetration stuctures are decreased when assessed for penetration ability on a given experimental substance/membrane.

A single species pathogen growth phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of pathogen penetration stuctures are increased when assessed for penetration ability on a given experimental substance/membrane.

A single species pathogen growth phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of pathogen penetration stuctures are decreased when assessed for penetration ability on a given experimental substance/membrane.

label.value: delayed timing of penetration structure formation

definition.value: A single species pathogen growth phenotype in which formation of pathogen specialized penetration structure begins later than normal when assessed for penetration ability on a given experimental substance/membrane.

A single species pathogen growth phenotype in which formation of pathogen specialized penetration structure begins sooner than normal when assessed for penetration ability on a given experimental substance/membrane.

label.value: abolished formation of pathogen penetration structure

definition.value: A single species pathogen growth phenotype in which the  ability of the pathogen to  form a specialized penetration structure is abolished when assessed for penetration ability on a given experimental substance/membrane.

label.value: delayed pathogen penetration across the barrier

definition.value: A single species pathogen growth phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of pathogen penetration begins later than normal when assessed for penetration ability on a given experimental substance/membrane.

label.value: increased pathogen penetration across the barrier

definition.value: A single species pathogen penetration phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of pathogen penetration of a given experimental substance/membrane is increased.

label.value: decreased pathogen penetration across the barrier

definition.value: A single species pathogen penetration phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of pathogen penetration of a given experimental substance/membrane is decreased

label.value: abolished pathogen growth after penetration of the barrier

definition.value: A single species phenotype in which the pathogen's ability to contine to grow after penetration of a given experimental substance/membrane in an in vitro assay is abolished.

label.value: increased pathogen growth after penetration of the barrier

definition.value: A single species phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of pathogen growth after penetration of a given experimental substance/membrane in an in vitro assay is increased.

label.value: decreased pathogen growth after penetration of the barrier

definition.value: A single species phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of pathogen growth after penetration of a given experimental substance/membrane in an in vitro assay is decreased.

label.value: delayed timing of pathogen growth after penetration of the barrier

definition.value: A single species phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of pathogen growth after penetration of a given experimental substance/membrane in an in vitro assay begins later than normal.

label.value: premature pathogen growth after penetration of the barrier

definition.value: A single species phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of pathogen growth after penetration of a given experimental substance/membrane in an in vitro assay begins sooner than normal.

A single species phenotype where the asexual reproductive developmental process whose specific outcome is the progression of structures that will be used in the process of creating new individuals, from their formation to the mature structures is abnormal (GO:0048608).

A reproductive phenotype where the process of endospore formation, in which a cell gives rise to an endospore, a dormant, highly resistant spore with a thick wall that forms within the mother cell is abnormal. Endospores are produced by some low G+C Gram-positive bacteria in response to harsh conditions. (GO:0034301)

label.value: premature pathogen penetration across the barrier

definition.value: A single species pathogen growth phenotype in which the frequency of occurrence of pathogen penetration begins sooner than normal when assessed for penetration ability on a given experimental substance/membrane.
A reproductive phenotype where the morphology of the asexual spore is abnormal (FAO:0000023). The product of mitosis.
A reproductive phenotype where the morphology of the asexual spore is normal (FAO:0000023). The product of mitosis.

A single species phenotype where the asexual reproductive developmental process whose specific outcome is the progression of structures that will be used in the process of creating new individuals, from their formation to the mature structures is normal (GO:0048608).
A reproductive phenotype where the morphology of the sexual spore is abnormal (FAO:0000017). The product of meiosis.

A pathogen host interaction phenotype which affects the binding of one pathogen protein to one host protein. The relevant proteins may include the one encoded by the mutated gene, or may both be encoded by different genes.
A single species phenotype that affects the binding of one protein to another. The relevant proteins may include the one encoded by the mutated gene, or may both be encoded by different genes.

This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

A single species molecular function phenotype in which the binding of one protein to another is abnormal. The relevant proteins may include the one encoded by the mutated gene, or may both be encoded by different genes.

A single species molecular function phenotype in which the binding of one protein to another is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). The relevant proteins may include the one encoded by the mutated gene, or may both be encoded by different genes.

A single species molecular function phenotype in which the binding of one protein to another does not occur. The relevant proteins may include the one encoded by the mutated gene, or may both be encoded by different genes.

A single species molecular function phenotype in which the binding of one protein to another occurs to a lower extent than normal. The relevant proteins may include the one encoded by the mutated gene, or may both be encoded by different genes.

A single species molecular function phenotype in which the binding of one protein to another occurs to a greater extent than normal. The relevant proteins may include the one encoded by the mutated gene, or may both be encoded by different genes.

A single species molecular function phenotype in which a mutation causes a gene product to bind to one or more proteins with different specificity from normal. For example, a protein may bind to a protein in a mutant that it does not bind in wild type. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.
no logical definition in FYPO for 'altered protein binding specificity'

A single species molecular function phenotype in which the binding of one protein to a protein complex is abnormal. The protein whose binding to the protein complex is affected may be encoded by the mutated gene, or may be encoded by a different gene.

A single species molecular function phenotype in which the binding of one protein to another occurs for a shorter time than normal. The relevant proteins may include the one encoded by the mutated gene, or may both be encoded by different genes.
logical definition needs checking.

label.value: decreased extent and duration of protein-protein interaction

definition.value: A single species molecular function phenotype in which the binding of one protein to another occurs to a lower extent, and for a shorter time, than normal. The relevant proteins may include the one encoded by the mutated gene, or may both be encoded by different genes.
logical definition needs checking.
A single organism phenotype that affects RNA binding. The relevant gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.
A single organism phenotype that affects DNA binding. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

A single species molecular function phenotype in which the binding of one protein to a protein complex is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). The protein whose binding to the protein complex is assayed may be encoded by the mutated gene, or may be encoded by a different gene.

A single organism (molecular function??) phenotype in which occurrence of DNA binding by a gene product is abnormal, when a gene or the bound DNA sequence is mutated. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

A single organism (molecular function??) phenotype in which occurrence of DNA binding by a gene product is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). The relevant gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.
Logical defintion quality (PATO:0000001) and (inheres_in some DNA binding (GO:0003677)) and (qualifier (??) some normal PATO:0000461)

A single organism (molecular function??) phenotype in which DNA binding by a gene product does not occur, when a gene or the bound DNA sequence is mutated. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

A single organism (molecular function??) phenotype in which a gene product that normally binds to a specific DNA sequence instead binds to a different sequence when a gene is mutated. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.
no logical definition for 'altered DNA binding specificity' in FYPO

A single organism (molecular function??) phenotype in which occurrence of DNA binding by a gene product is decreased, when a gene or the bound DNA sequence is mutated. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

A single organism (molecular function??) phenotype in which occurrence of DNA binding by a gene product is increased, when a gene or the bound DNA sequence is mutated. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

label.value: abnormal multiple protein binding to DNA

definition.value: A single organism (molecular function??) phenotype in which the binding of two or more proteins to DNA is abnormal. The proteins may bind simultaneously or sequentially, but both or all would normally be present together on DNA at some time. One affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or all may be encoded by different genes.
no logical definition for 'abnormal multiple protein binding to DNA' in FYPO

A single organism (molecular function??) phenotype in which occurrence of RNA binding by a gene product is abnormal, when a gene or the bound RNA sequence is mutated. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

A single organism (molecular function??) phenotype in which occurrence of RNA binding by a gene product is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). The relevant gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

A single organism (molecular function??) phenotype in which RNA binding by a gene product does not occur, when a gene or the bound RNA sequence is mutated. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

A single organism (molecular function??) phenotype in which occurrence of RNA binding by a gene product is decreased, when a gene or the bound RNA sequence is mutated. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

A single organism (molecular function??) phenotype in which occurrence of RNA binding by a gene product is increased, when a gene or the bound RNA sequence is mutated. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.
A single species phenotype that affects the binding of a gene product to another substance. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

A single species phenotype in which the amount, distribution, composition or morphology of a cell part is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
